e characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Coudray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Channel Islands:  see  Cowdrey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cowdrey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Coudrai in Seine-Maritime, France, or Coudray in Eure, France, or from Cowdray or Cowdry in Sussex, England. The latter was probably named after one of the places in France. All are named with Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’ (a collective noun from <i>coudre</i> ‘hazelnut tree’, Late Latin <i>colurus</i>, a metathesized form of classical Latin <i>corylus</i>, from Greek <i>korylos</i>). Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’, adopted into English, denoting someone who lived near a hazel copse."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Coudray was born in Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Joan de Meoulis. In 1170, his occupation is listed as praepositus of domfront in Domfront, Oise, Picardie, France. He died about 1220."},"et":{"–about 1220":"–umbes 1220","–Female":"Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","–1220":"–1220","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1170":"1170","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Domfront, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–about 1220":"–noin 1220","–Female":"Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","–1220":"–1220","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"noin 1200","about 1220":"noin 1220","1170":"1170","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Domfront, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Oise, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"–about 1220":"–environ 1220","–Female":"Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","–1220":"–1220","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"environ 1200","about 1220":"environ 1220","1170":"1170","England":"Angleterre","Normandy, France":"Normandie, France","Domfront, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Oise, Picardie, France","lifeSummary":"William de Coudray est né à Normandie, France. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Joan de Meoulis. En 1170, sa profession de son indiquée est praepositus of domfront à Domfront, Oise, Picardie, France. Il est décédé environ 1220."},"de":{"–about 1220":"–um 1220","–Female":"Verstorben","1200–Male":"1200–Verstorben","–1220":"–1220","1200":"1200","1220":"1220","about 1200":"um 1200","about 1220":"um 1220","1170":"1170","England":"England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankreich","Domfront, Normandy, France":"Domfront, Oise, Picardie, Frankreich","lifeSummary":"William de Coudray wurde in Normandie, Frankreich geboren. Er hatte mit Joan de Meoulis mindestens 1 Sohn. 1170 ist sein Beruf als praepositus of domfront in Domfront, Oise, Picardie, Frankreich aufgeführt. Er starb um 1220."},"ht":{"–about 1220":"–